  "text": "Regarding its \"colour, \" this SEL will not peak like the YB because there is no \"pumping action\" of a laser in [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] as it occurs in the PL when the YB appears. The FET-like devices of [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] were placed in the dark to observe their weak EL, which only appears when holes are injected near the GaN surface. Therefore, the spectrum of their SEL will reflect the exponential increase in ( ) as we go from the CB to the VB in Figure 4 , which is the counterpart of Figure 2 for surface Device no. 1 acting as a photon emitter and not as the photon absorber it was in Figure 2 . Hence, this SEL will not peak at peak ≈ 2.2 eV as the YB of the PL does. Instead, it will show an exponential decay in intensity as the energy of the emitted photons increases. To be precise, this SEL has to show an intensity proportional to exp(−ℎ]/ 0 ); thus, it will possess the same slope shown in Figure 2 , though decreasing with photon energy h because the density ( ) in the GaN surface decreases as exp(−ℎ]/ 0 ) when we go from the VB to the CB. This ( ) ∝ exp(−ℎ]/ 0 ) was obtained in Section 2 from the PC data of [CITATION_5] obtained 17 years ago, and this SEL observed recently in [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] is the empirical proof we promised in Section 2 of its validity, which is ensured when we consider that 0 was between 230 meV and 280 meV [CITATION_8] . Figure 4 shows a sketch of the weak EL spectrum shown in Figure 3 (b) of [CITATION_9] . For 0 = 230 meV, we have 0 ≈ 2600 K which means that the slope of Figure 4 will be tg( ) = −1/ 0 , as if this SEL was the EL derived from a hot-electron gas at eq ≈ 2600 K. This is the explanation provided in [CITATION_10] for the decay of the weak EL the authors observed with this eq . Unaware of the Device no. 1 existing at n-GaN surfaces, these authors propose that the weak EL they observe is derived from a hot-electron gas in the GaN channel at this eq ≈ 2600 K, an effect that our model does not require at all. This eq in [CITATION_11] confirms that the PC data of [CITATION_12] , with a proper model for Device no. 1, reveal the density of surface states at the surface of n-GaN devices, as we have proposed. This is good proof of the validity of the relationship ( ) ∝ exp(−ℎ]/ 0 ) derived using our model from the PC data obtained long ago [CITATION_13] , though it has not been well understood until now. Although the time evolution of this SEL moving from the gate contact to drain one after some delay from the application of a sufficiently high DS [CITATION_14] provides additional proof about the origin and usefulness of this SEL as a marker for surface charge in n-GaN devices, we will consider this point further due to the space constraint of this paper.",
